<TITLE> Russia's Putin says to "play till the last second" </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Sept 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russian President Vladimir Putin said on Monday he would "play till the last second", making clear he should not be written off as a lame duck as he prepares to step down next year. Putin, serving his second term, has said he will respect the two-term limit set out in Russia's constitution. Most observers expect him to say whom he favours to replace him, almost assuring that candidate victory in the 2008 presidential vote. "In our country, nearly everyone loves ice hockey. We know the way real professionals play -- till the last second," Russia's Vesti-24 channel showed Putin telling journalists during a visit to the United Arab Emirates. "And so I will work in the same way and will do whatever I can so that all the ministers, the whole government, the (presidential) administration work precisely in this style." Putin, highly popular at home, has not named his favoured successor yet. Analysts say this may be a deliberate ploy to ward off the "lame duck syndrome" that can afflict heads of state as they near the end of their final term. Opinion polls place first deputy prime ministers Sergei Ivanov and Dmitry Medvedev as the favourites to replace Putin. Analysts, however, say Putin could endorse a less well-known member of his team for the top Kremlin job. Putin says he will not leave the stage altogether and will continue playing an important role in Russian politics. But he has not specified what that role will 
